body:
There is not much to do by hand. If you download the csv file and name it "data.csv", then you can do

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[active,tightpage]{preview}
\usepackage{pgfplots}
\pgfplotsset{compat=newest}
\PreviewEnvironment{tikzpicture} 

\definecolor{tb_color_1}{RGB}{245,124,0}
\definecolor{tb_color_2}{RGB}{0,167,247}

\pgfplotscreateplotcyclelist{tb}{
semithick,tb_color_1\\%
semithick,tb_color_2\\%
}

\begin{document}
  \begin{tikzpicture}
    \begin{axis}[cycle list name=tb, 
                 grid=both,
                 grid style={solid,gray!30!white},
                 axis lines=middle,
                 xlabel={step},
                 ylabel={value},
                 x label style={at={(axis description cs:0.5,-0.1)},anchor=north},
                 y label style={at={(axis description cs:-0.1,.5)},rotate=90,anchor=south},]
      \addplot table [x=Step, y=Value, col sep=comma] {data.csv};
    \end{axis}
  \end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```
and get
![tb_latex](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/6756603/24898814/6634ede0-1e9e-11e7-9d98-3964508b88fe.png)

But indeed, it would be nice to also export the smoothed values.
